      {
        "id": "-bGLNMxEmuSSqGx_",
        "title": "Text 9",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Explore (Digging In)</strong></p><p><em>Providing for Individual Needs</em></p><p>Have<strong> Learning Aid Template: Blank 100s Grids</strong> and <strong>Learning Aid Template: Blank Grids and tape Diagrams</strong> available for students to use as needed.</p><p><strong>Suggested Questions</strong></p><ul><li>The total in the table is 30 students. To predict the number with a widow&#x27;s peak for a new total, would a new percent bar help?</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "r_IV1LRyv_1cvMSf",
        "title": "Text 14",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Yes.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "_8IsihQanWFdLoo0",
        "title": "Text 15",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>Where would you put the 500 on this percent bar?</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "PWCANl9TjTl8Sw5S",
        "title": "Text 16",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>500 would be above 100% at the right-hand end of the percent bar because both represent the total.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "bCwr0XeGpMtiwk9B",
        "title": "Text 17",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>You found that the percentage of students with a widow&#x27;s peak was 60% for the given data. Where would 60% go on your new percent bar? </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "Zjs9dII7N_MSwwsQ",
        "title": "Text 18",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>60% would be at the sixth increment of 10%. </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "KXlDhubeD_VKsddo",
        "title": "Text 19",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>how much is 60% of 500? </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "aKxfafvbLOXjIHGI",
        "title": "Text 20",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Since 10% of 500 is 50, 60% would be 300. </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "PkbIcudEpZje1SA_",
        "title": "Text 21",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Some students msy use equivalent ratios, rate tables, unit rates, percent bars, or double number lines to answer the Initial Challenge. Watch for additional strategies that be can shared during the Summarize. (portrayal)</p><p>What If...? Situation A is important since it connects to the 1% strategy. Be prepares to help students (or even whole class) interpret the percent bar in the What If...?. (Language)</p><p>As students work on What If...? Situation A, observe their strategies. There are two ways to determine the equivalent ratios: according to percentage or according to the total. Both strategies are good ones and worth discussing. </p><p><strong>Equivalent Ratios: Finding the Students for Every 1%:</strong> Some students use the strategy of finding 1%, 5%, 10%, 25%, or some other convenient percentage that has a &quot;friendly&quot; scaling equivalent. In this case, 1% of 30 students is 0.3 students, or as a unit rate, 0.3 students per 1% of the class. Using this thinking, a student can scale up to the number of students to determine the percentage. </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "NQNw9dNOEvT-q8A9",
        "title": "Scaling using for Every 1%",
        "content": {
          "type": "Image",
          "url": "cq/images/scaling-using-for-every-1-.png",
          "filename": "cq/images/scaling-using-for-every-1-.png"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "PybEBsFK0IIandpr",
        "title": "Text 22",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Equivalent Ratios: Finding the Percent for Every 1 Student: </strong>Some students will partition according to the total number of students in the class. Rather than finding how many students (or what fraction of a student) make up 1% of a class, these students will find what percent of the class 1 student is. They will likely divide 100% ÷ 30 and get that 1 student is approximately 3.3% if the class, or as a unit rate, 1 student per 3.3% of the class. </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "eUXYlZvflVMEAgBP",
        "title": "Scaling Using for Every 1 Student",
        "content": {
          "type": "Image",
          "url": "cq/images/scaling-using-for-every-1-student.png",
          "filename": "cq/images/scaling-using-for-every-1-student.png"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "DJbi_JpWaXcgpEFv",
        "title": "Text 23",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Note that students&#x27; strategies used to partition in each of the ways outlines previously so that you can have students present their strategies in the Summarize. Also note any novel strategies that students use. These may come out as students work on What If...? Situation A (6), where they are trying to show how Sharon may have used the same thinking without using a bar diagram.</p><ul><li>When you make a rate table, what would the two row labels be? </li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "QCFJ10r64_AQ19WQ",
        "title": "Text 13",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>We might set up a table as follows: </p>"
