        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>Either way, we can find what percent 12 is of 30.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4xU-F-gEsNJA1ZcS",
        "title": "Text 27",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<ul><li>How does your rate table resemble a percent bar? A double number line? Scaling the ratio?</li></ul>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "sQpLI_vLNahDzLsK",
        "title": "Text 24",
        "display": "teacher",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p>All involve pairing up the known data and then partitioning and multiplying.</p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "y0SyGroKahRuUu01",
        "title": "Text 11",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Planning for the Summary</strong></p><p>What evidence will you use in the summary to clarify and deepen understanding of the Now What Do You Know? Question? What will you do if you do not have evidence? </p>"
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "C9y5JfQ4_XSCSjUN",
        "title": "Text 12",
        "content": {
          "type": "Text",
          "format": "html",
          "text": [
            "<p><strong>Now What Do You Know?</strong></p><p>how does finding 1% help you scale to another percent? </p><p>How is using a percent bar like using a rate table? </p>"
          ]
        }
      }
